@node about " Password Check v1.1 by Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS""
@prev main
@{"°°" link grems}
   ___  _              _
  / _ \| |__  ___ _  _| |_
 |  _  | '_ \/ _ \ || |  _|
 |_| |_|_.__/\___/\_,_|\__|                          @{b}(c) GREMLiNS MAXsWARE@{ub}

 This is a slight  update to v1.0 of PassWord Check ('97).  Every 20 calls
 the user makes to the BBS (..if any of you SysOp's are lucky enough), the
 door is run and asks the user if they would like to change their password
 and gives the option to do so, or not. It's as simple as that..

@endnode
@node run " Password Check v1.1 by Glen Martin of GREMLiNS BBS""
@{"°°" link grems}
  ___         _        _ _
 |_ _|_ _  __| |_ __ _| | |
  | || ' \(_-<  _/ _` | | |
 |___|_||_/__/\__\__,_|_|_|                          @{b}(c) GREMLiNS MAXsWARE@{ub}

 Firstly (if you already haven't) create a new directory called "gremlins"
 in your doors directory. Assign "gremlins" to your doors path in the user
 startup sequence, eg: "assign gremlins: doors:gremlins" assuming you have
 the doors path assigned also, which is always a must.

 Move the "PW_Check" directory (you unpacked) into the "gremlins" dir  and
 setup the door to run via the "Introdoor.text" door sequence. Below is an
 example and that's it.

 Example:  gremlins:pw_check/pw_check

 To test the door, set your calls to 20 and login.  Or simply set it up to
 run from a menu key and play around with it, too easy. Each time the door
 is run, it creates a logfile in your "LogFiles" dir.

@endnode
